did.unittitle: Office of the Dean of Undergraduate Education Records

origination.label: Creator
origination.corpname: Associate Dean for Undergraduate Curriculum Development

arrangement.head: Arrangement
arrangement.p: This collection is organized into eight series: Subject files; Committees; Publications; Plan of study; Student files; Degree sheets; Dean of Undergraduate Education records; and Unprocessed accessions.

processinfo.head: Processing Information
processinfo.p: In the plan of study series, there is a divider indicating "current students," between folders 81 and 82 (between date ranges 78-82 and 83-85) which I believe is in the correct location, but there is another divider indicating "withdrawn students," which seems to have been moved at some point because it is now at the end of the box. An internship folder in Box 6 contains correspondence dating from 77-80. The internship booklet in Box 12 was added with the publication series. ACL folders (Plan of study course number) from subject files were moved to the plan of study series because they contained the same material as the administrative files in the plan of study series. Committee Folders found in the Subject Files were moved to the Committee Files series. Within subject files, files of sample mailings were relabeled so that they would all be together under 'Mailing, etc.' For example "Freshmen mailing, Fall '78" was reworded as "Mailing, Freshmen, Fall '78". In October 2020, Jane Kelly, Records and Accessioning Archivist, processed accession 2011.050, the Dean of Undergraduate Education records.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: The collection contains subject files, committee records, administrative and student records from the plan of study program, publications from the Office of the Dean of Undergraduate Studies, and records from the Dean of Undergraduate Education.

bioghist.head: Biographical / Historical
bioghist.p: In about 2014, the office restructured and changed its name to the Office of Academic Advising and Undergraduate Studies, which encompasses the Associate Deans of Undergraduate Education, the Academic Resource Center, and professional advising staff. The office provides academic support, educational programs, and opportunities for research and post-graduate fellowships for graduate students and undergraduates in the schools of Arts & Sciences and Engineering.

accessrestrict.head: Conditions Governing Access
accessrestrict.p: This collection contains some restricted material. Restrictions related to specific material are listed in the detailed contents list. This collection may require review before it is available for use. Please contact DCA for further details.

userestrict.head: Conditions Governing Use
userestrict.p: Some material in this collection may be protected by copyright and other rights. Please see "Reproductions and Use" on the Digital Collections and Archives website for more information about reproductions and permission to publish. Copyright to all materials created by Tufts University employees in the course of their work is held by the Trustees of Tufts University.

prefercite.head: Preferred Citation
prefercite.p: Office of the Dean of Undergraduate Education Records, 1940 -- 2018. Tufts University. Digital Collections and Archives. Medford, MA.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: This series consists of subject files, arranged alphabetically dating predominantly from the 1970s through the 1980s. The files contain correspondence including related statistics, administrative records, forms, and reports.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: This series contains files of Plan of Study/Independent Study majors. The files consist of student folders including applications for plans of study and administrative files.

arrangement.head: Arrangement
arrangement.p: Alphabetically ordered administrative files were placed at the beginning of the series.

Student files were kept in original order but we were unable to figure out precisely what original order meant. Originally, several student file folders were grouped by a sticky note and often a rubber band. The sticky note indicated a range of years that a student's application was received/accepted into the Plan of Study program. Range of years could possibly also indicate years of graduation. Possibly, the plans of study files were arranged alphabetically by year that the students' plans were accepted or rejected. This means that there is some year overlap between the alphabetical arrangements as there may have been some toing and froing between the student and committee before a plan was finally approved. A plan may have submitted in '78 but may not have been approved until '82 due to recommendations and revisions. We preserved these sub-groupings but added the information contained on each respective sticky note (e.g., date range) to every folder in a group. The folders in each group were then alphabetized.

acqinfo.head: Immediate Source of Acquisition
acqinfo.p: Transferred by the Office of the Dean of Undergraduate Education, September 2010, accession 2011.050.

arrangement.head: Arrangement
arrangement.p: This series is arranged in received order in one sub-series: Jim Glaser records.

processinfo.head: Processing Information
processinfo.p: This series was processed by Jane Kelly, Records and Accessioning Archivist, in October 2020. Each top-level folder served as the basis for a zip file, and the Records and Accessioning Archivist created metadata for each zip file. Files were zipped using 7-Zip and ingested to the Dark Archive. A file-level inventory was created, and series and collection-level description were updated at the time of processing.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: This series contains records created or compiled by Jim Glaser, Dean of Undergraduate Education from approximately 2003 through 2010. These records include reports, meeting agendas and minutes, resolutions, committee documents, data, communications, and memos. Records include information on academic policies and programs, the undergraduate experience, teaching awards, scholarships, and the reorganization of the School of Arts, Sciences, & Engineering.
